\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Hom-Complex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Hom-Complex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-complexes.
 We define their 
\series bold
hom-complex
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}^{\star}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-complex whose underlying graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module has homogeneous component in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R,i}^{\star}(X,Y)=\{\varphi\colon X\to Y\mid\varphi\text{ is a graded \ensuremath{R}-linear of degree }i\}.
\]

\end_inset

whose differential, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}_{X,Y}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{d}_{X,Y}^{\star}(\varphi)=\mathrm{d}_{Y}\varphi-(-1)^{|\varphi|}\varphi\mathrm{d}_{X}.\label{eq:homcomplexdifferential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all homogeneous 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}^{\star}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is understood from context, then we simplify our notation by saying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to mean 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 If in addition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 commutes with the differentials (or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}^{\star}(\varphi)=0$
\end_inset

), then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-chain map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are understood from context, then we simplify our notation even more by
 dropping 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 in the subscripts of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}_{X,Y}^{\star}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}_{Y}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 With this notational convention in mind, we may rewrite 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homcomplexdifferential})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in a much cleaner format:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{d}^{\star}(\varphi)=\mathrm{d}\varphi-(-1)^{|\varphi|}\varphi\mathrm{d}\label{eq:homcomplexdifferential2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sign 
\begin_inset Formula $-(-1)^{|\varphi|}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homcomplexdifferential2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 may seem a little unusual at first glance.
 Indeed, the differential for the tensor compex 
\begin_inset Formula $X\otimes_{R}Y$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}^{\otimes}(x\otimes y)=\mathrm{d}(x)\otimes y+(-1)^{|x|}x\otimes\mathrm{d}(y)
\]

\end_inset

for all homogeneous 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 In fact , if we had replaced 
\begin_inset Formula $-(-1)^{|\varphi|}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homcomplexdifferential})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{|\varphi|}$
\end_inset

, then we would still still obtain a differential.
 So why should we change things up here? One of the reasons is that it allows
 us to interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}^{\star}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

 as measuring the failure of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to be an 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-chain map.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-chain map if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\varphi=(-1)^{|\varphi|}\varphi\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 if and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\ker\mathrm{d}^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, two 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-chain maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 are homotopy equivalent if and only if there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $(i+1)$
\end_inset

-map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi=\mathrm{d}\phi+(-1)^{|\phi|}\phi\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi\in\mathrm{im}\,\mathrm{d^{\star}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the homology of the hom-complex has a really nice interpretation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{H}_{i}(\mathrm{Hom}_{R}^{\star}(X,Y))=\{\text{homotopy classes of \ensuremath{i}-chain maps }X\to Y\}.
\]

\end_inset

This is probably the most important reason we use the 
\begin_inset Formula $-(-1)^{|\varphi|}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homcomplexdifferential2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
When an 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-map is a chain map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-complexes and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 is a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}^{\star}(\varphi)\colon A\to\Sigma B$
\end_inset

 is a chain map since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}_{\Sigma B}\mathrm{d}^{\star}(\varphi) & =\mathrm{d}_{\Sigma B}(\mathrm{d}_{B}\varphi-\varphi\mathrm{d}_{A})\\
 & =-\mathrm{d}_{\Sigma B}\varphi\mathrm{d}\\
 & =\mathrm{d}_{B}\varphi\mathrm{d}_{A}\\
 & =(\mathrm{d}_{B}\varphi-\varphi\mathrm{d}_{A})\mathrm{d}_{A}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we have a short exact sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-complexes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{gradedrmaptochainmapseq2}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=50] 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A  
\backslash
arrow[r,"  
\backslash
mathrm{d} ^{
\backslash
star } (
\backslash
varphi)  "]  & 
\backslash
Sigma B 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
pi "] & 
\backslash
Sigma B 
\backslash
slash 
\backslash
mathrm{im } ( 
\backslash
mathrm{d} ^{
\backslash
star } (
\backslash
varphi)) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which in turn induces the following long exact sequence in homology:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagram333}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=50, column sep=50 ]  && 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
